title Sala B1 landed GREEN — a session carried live over Comlink, the SLC flagship's L2
prompt Keaton said "kg" after Pool P1; the recommend line named Sala B1 (live carriage over Comlink, unblocked by Pool P0) as the most direct step toward the SLC flagship's live broadcast.
think this is the lap the whole SLC/go-to-market strategy points at -- the live broadcast a creator does from their phone. Built it green rather than described it, stacking on the same Pool branch so it ships with P0/P1.
think composed rather than invented: the log and replay are Sala B0; the seal is Comlink's wire_format; the carriage shape (source/follower/selftest/demo over real UDP) mirrors the Neth carriage lap already proven, including its compact-payload-vs-hex-line lesson (a session event line hex-doubles past the 340-byte sealed datagram, so the event crosses in receipt_core's compact binary payload and the follower reconstructs the exact signed line).
think added append_signed_line to sala_session_core.rye additively -- the follower holds only the broadcaster's public key, so it cannot re-sign; it appends the carried, already-signed line and replay verifies the whole. Confirmed Sala B0's own witness stays green after the additive edit.
think made the carriage-transparency claim exact: build_event_payload signs the SAME FactFields sala.append_event signs (from=actor, amount=seq, memo=payload, stamp), so the reconstructed line is byte-identical to the direct one, so the follower's replayed session root equals the source's own -- carriage changes nothing about the fold. Proven in-process (selftest) and over real UDP with three ordered events (demo).
think witnessed order preservation implicitly and correctly: the source sends events seq 1,2,3 in order, the follower appends in receipt order, and sala.replay enforces the strictly-increasing sequence -- so any reordering by carriage would be caught as OutOfOrder. This is the ordered-stream property (Mycelium's concern) the broadcast needs.
think ran the two-subprocess demo over actual localhost UDP: source broadcast 3 sealed events in order, follower replayed them and sealed its root back, source checked it against its own independently-computed root -- matched. A real broadcast crossed a real wire.
think wired B1 into parity_ch01.rish and re-ran Sala B0, Sala B1, Pool P0, Pool P1 together -- all GREEN, no regression from the additive append_signed_line.
obs three real green laps this session's build stretch (Pool P0, Pool P1, Sala B1) -- the design layer has caught down to the build, and the SLC flagship's live-broadcast experience (L2) now runs end to end over a real hop.
obs "kg" is keep-going, not "send" -- so P0, P1, and B1 all rest on the branch awaiting Keaton's send word.
